  constitutionalism, arguing that democratic processes rather than judicial
  review are the proper guardians of constitutional principles. Drawing on
  republican tradition, Bellamy contends that constitutional norms emerge from
  and are sustained by democratic political contestation rather than being
  imposed from outside political practice. Constitutional traditions are living
  practices embodied in democratic institutions, not fixed legal texts.

  RELEVANCE: Crucial for understanding the relationship between constitutional
  traditions and democratic governance. Bellamy's argument that constitutional
  norms emerge from political practice rather than transcending it illuminates
  how constitutional traditions function and can fail. His emphasis on
